section.para:
      Guards are a possibility to reduce the amount of nesting.  Heavily nested
code is much harder to read.

Bad:
  public void foo() {
if (conditionA) {
  if (conditionB) {
      if (conditionC) {
    // do some work
      }
  } else {
      throw new MyException();
  }
}
}

Good:
  public void foo() {
if (!conditionA) {
return;
}

if (!conditionB) {
throw new MyException();
}

if (!conditionC) {
return;
}

// do some work
}

Use interfaces or the abstract base class instead of concrete implementation classes where possible.
Don't write: ArrayList<String> names = new ArrayList<String>();
Instead use the interface name: List<String> names = new ArrayList<String>();
This is especially important in method signatures.

Always use
 Type[] arrayName;

instead of the C-like
Type arrayName[];
